{{Infobox museum | name = Fernand Léger Museum | native_name = Musée national Fernand Léger | native_name_lang = fr | image = Musee Fernand Leger 01.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | alt = façade of the museum, with coloured mosaic | map_type = | map_caption = | map_alt = | map_size = | coordinates = {{coord|43.6222|7.1129|display=inline,title}} | established = 1960 | dissolved = | location = [[Biot, Alpes-Maritimes]], France | type = art museum | collection = paintings, designs, ceramics, bronzes and tapestries of [[Fernand Léger]]. | visitors = | director = | president = | curator = | owner = | publictransit = | car_park = | network = | website = {{url|en.musees-nationaux-alpesmaritimes.fr/fleger}} }}
[[File:Grande fleur musee fernand leger.JPG|thumb|Sculpture in the gardens of the museum]] The '''Fernand Léger Museum''', {{lang-fr|'''Musée national Fernand Léger'''|italic=no}}, is a French national museum in [[Biot, Alpes-Maritimes]], in south-eastern France. It is dedicated to the work of the twentieth-century artist [[Fernand Léger]]. Although originally privately owned, it is now a state museum entitled to style itself [[Musée de France]].
==History== In 1955, Fernand Léger bought a villa in Biot, called Mas Saint-Andre, and died soon afterwards.<ref name=ParisDigest>{{Cite web |url= https://www.parisdigest.com/french_riviera/leger_museum_biot.htm|title= Leger Museum in Biot. Facts. Visits.|author= | year=2018 |publisher=Paris Digest |accessdate=2018-10-22}}</ref> The museum was built on the property after the death of the artist in 1955 by [[Nadia Léger]] and {{ill|Georges Bauquier|fr}}, to designs by the architect [[Andreï Svetchine]]; an earlier design by [[Paul Nelson (architect)|Paul Nelson]] had been rejected. Construction began in 1957, and the museum opened in 1960.{{r|self}} The gardens were designed by [[Henri Fish]] and contain sculptures based on Léger's work.{{r|self2}}
