The '''William V. Kelley-Roosevelt Asiatic Expedition''' was a zoological expedition to southeast Asia in 1928–1929 sponsored by the [[Field Museum of Natural History]] and organized by [[Kermit Roosevelt]] and his brother [[Theodore Roosevelt, Jr.]]
==Funding and organization== William Vallangdiham Kelley (1861–1932), a Field Museum trustee and benefactor,<ref>{{cite book|editor=Goodspeed, Arthur Weston|editor2=Healy, Daniel David|chapter=William Vallangdiham Kelley|title=History of Cook County, Illinois|volume=vol. I|year=1909|pages=690–691|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tQRJAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA690}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Museum given $50,000 in will of W. V. Kelley|date=28 January 1932|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1932/01/28/page/22/article/museum-given-50-000-in-will-of-w-v-kelley}}</ref> financed the expedition, which was extremely well equipped. There were three separate sections of the expedition — one led by the two Roosevelt brothers,<ref name="RooseveltsSection">{{cite journal|author=Osgood, W. H.|title=Mammals of the Kelley-Roosevelts expedition to French Indo-China|journal=Fieldiana Zoology|year=1932|url=https://archive.org/details/mammalsofkelleyr1810osgo}}</ref> another conducted by the British ornithologist Herbert Stevens,<ref name="StevensSection">{{cite journal|author=Bangs, Outram|authorlink=Outram Bangs|title=Birds of western China obtained by the Kelley-Roosevelts expedition|journal=Fieldiana Zoology|volume=18|issue=11|year=1931|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsofwesternch1811bang}}</ref> and another led by [[Harold Jefferson Coolidge, Jr.|H. J. Coolidge]].<ref name="HaiphongSection">{{cite journal|author=Bangs, Outram|title=Birds of the Kelley-Roosevelts expedition to French-Indo-china|journal=Fieldiana Zoology|year=1931|volume=18|issue=3|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsofkelleyroo183bang}}</ref> The mammalogist [[Wilfred Hudson Osgood|W. H. Osgood]] described the expedition's collection of mammalian skins and designated the Roosevelt brothers' section as the first, Stevens's as the second, and Coolidge's as the third. The first section consisted of the two Roosevelt brothers with the photographer C. Suydam Cutting<ref>[http://siarchives.si.edu/collections/siris_arc_296615 Charles Suydam Cutting (1889–1972), Smithsonian Institution Archives]</ref> and their Chinese interpreter.<ref name=RooseveltsSection/>
==Itinerary== Stevens accompanied the Roosevelts up the [[Irrawaddy River|Irrawaddy]] to the Chinese-Burma border and then in January 1929 went north from [[Tengchong|Tengyueh]] with his own caravan. During all of February he collected specimens at the Lijiang bend.<ref>[http://www.travelchinaguide.com/attraction/yunnan/lijiang/shigu_drum.htm Lijiang Stone Drum and First Bend of Yangtze River, Yunnan]</ref> He then moved north to collect in [[Sichuan]] and spent May in the [[Wuxi County|Wushi hills]]. After some further collecting he went down the [[Yangtze]] to [[Shanghai]], sending 2,400 specimens to the Field Museum.<ref>[http://plants.jstor.org/stable/10.5555/al.ap.person.bm000332629 Stevens. Herbert (fl. 1925-1932), Herbarium, Natural History Museum (British Museum)]</ref> After separating from Stevens's section of the expedition, the Roosevelt brothers with Suydam Cutting went rapidly north to collect specimens of the [[giant panda]]. The Roosevelts hunted large mammals that were especially rare. Their party proceeded through [[Burma]] to [[Bhamo]] and northward to [[Kangding|Tatsienlu]] thence to [[Muping District|Mouping]]. Then going southward through [http://www.geographic.org/geographic_names/name.php?uni=-2699175&fid=1052&c=china Yachow], they crossed the [[Qingyi River (Sichuan)|Qingyi]] (Tung<ref>{{cite book|author=Little, Archibald John|year=1906|page=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TqE7Q8SwHcwC&pg=PA1|title=Across Yunnan & Tonking}}</ref>) River and continued their journey traveling slightly east of the [[Panlong River]] and reaching the railhead at [[Kunming|Yunnanfu]]. From there, Kermit Roosevelt returned to the United States upon an urgent request. Theodore Roosevelt, Jr. and Suydam Cutting continued to the vicinity of Saigon to procure specimens of [[banteng]], [[seladang]], and [[water buffalo]].<ref name=RooseveltsSection/>
{{quotation|The third section of the expedition devoted itself to concentrated work in northern [[French Indochina|Indo-China]], mainly in the province of [[Tonkin]]. Under the leadership of Harold J. Coolidge, Jr., a party of four was organized in which Russell W. Hendee was the mammalogist, [[Josselyn Van Tyne]] ornithologist, and Ralph E. Wheeler physician and parasitologist. After a brief stop in [[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]], where collections were made near [[Quảng Trị|Quangtri]], this party proceeded to [[Haiphong]] and [[Hanoi]] and thence up the valley of the Rivière Noire. They passed on into Northern Laos and worked there from a base at [[Phongsali|Phong Saly]], finally descending the [[Mekong River]] with a short stop at [[Vientiane]] to [[Savannakhet|Savannaket]] and thence overland to [[Hue]].<ref name=RooseveltsSection/>}}
Hendee departed from Coolidge's party in Laos on 14 May 1929 and started down the Mekong to join Theodore Roosevelt, Jr. and Suydam Cutting in [[Saigon]] but shortly after his departure he suffered a severe attack of malarial fever. Taken to a hospital in Vientiane on June 3, Hendee died on June 6.<ref name=RooseveltsSection/><ref>{{cite journal|author=Bailey, Afred M.|authorlink=Alfred Marshall Bailey|title=Obituary. Russell W. Hendee|journal=[[The Condor (journal)|The Condor]]|year=1930|volume=32|issue=3|pages=147–151|jstor=1363446|doi=10.2307/1363446}}</ref>
==Discoveries and collections== Coolidge's section of the expedition discovered a new mammalian species [[Roosevelt's muntjac]]<ref name=RooseveltsSection/> and a new avian species [[grey-faced tit-babbler|''Macronus kelleyi'']].<ref name=HaiphongSection/>
The expedition brought back several living specimens for the U.S. [[National Zoological Park (United States)|National Zoological Park]]: {{quotation|Through Theodore Roosevelt, jr., Harold S. Coolidge, jr., and Ralph Wheeler, all of the Kelley-Roosevelt expedition, were presented a trio of white-faced gibbons, father, mother, and child, all magnificent specimens; a rare Bay Bamboo rat; a sun bear; a Himalayan bear; as well as several smaller specimens.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Report of the Director of the National Zoological Park for the Year Ended June 30, 1930|page=84|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lXo2AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA84-A1}}</ref>}}
The expedition collected approximately 5000 bird skins. {{quotation|A collection of more than 5000 specimens were gathered by the Kelley-Roosevelts Expedition of the Field Museum, in unexplored regions of Siam, French Indo-China, and the interior of Southern China. The work in China was carried on by Theodore Roosevelt '08, and his brother, Kermit Roosevelt '12, and by Suydam Cutting '12. The Indo-China Expedition, led by H. J. Coolidge Jr. '27, included Dr. Ralph E. Wheeler '22, M.D. '26 and Dr. Josselyn Van Tyne '25. These six out of the eight members of the expedition were Harvard men. ... The birds were collected mostly by shooting and by use of ingenious native traps set in the forest at night. The skins were all prepared in the field and many of them transported over a thousand miles down rivers, along mountain trails, in the rainy season, before they could be shipped home. They arrived in perfect condition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1930/1/22/harvard-men-discover-new-species-of/|date=22 January 1930|newspaper=[[The Harvard Crimson]]|title=Harvard men discover new species of birds}} (Claims of discovery of new species have been challenged by [[molecular phylogenetics]].)</ref>}}
The expedition collected about 2,000 specimens of small mammals and 40 big mammals, including two giant panda skins (a first for Western museum collectors). The Roosevelt brothers shot and collected one panda and purchased a panda skin from a local hunter. The taxidermic panda specimens are on display in the Hall of Asian Mammals in the Field Museum.<ref>[http://www.fieldmuseum.org/theodore-and-kermit-roosevelt Theodore and Kermit Roosevelt, The Field Museum]></ref>
==Recounting the expedition== {{quotation|The lure of exploration through one of the few remaining corners of the world which Is little known, the Chinese-Tibetan frontier, brought 3,000 persons to the Field museum yesterday to hear Kermit Roosevelt. Actually only half of that number heard his lecture, a line of more than 1,500 being turned away when the auditorium was filled to capacity. Slides and motion pictures showed how the William V. Kelley-Roosevelt party abandoned their pack and ridIng animals and went on foot over mountain passes as high as 17,100 feet<ref>17100 feet ≈ 5212 meters.</ref> in what they thought would be a futile effort to kill a giant panda. Mr. Roosevelt and his brother, Col. Theodore Roosevelt, finally shot one of the animals, which will be placed on exhibit in the museum here. [[Yi people|The natives of the nearby village In Lololand]]{{Citation needed|reason=Source need for the location of the killed Giant Panda|date=July 2017}}, between Tibet and China, held purification rites after the party had shot their prize and taken it through the village. The panda is considered a semi-divinity, and never killed by the natives.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kermit Roosevelt tells crowd about his Asiatic hunting|date=2 December 1929|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1929/12/02/page/37/article/kermit-roosevelt-tells-crowd-about-his-asiatic-hunting}}</ref>}}
Kermit and Ted Roosevelt recounted their experiences in their book ''Trailing the Giant Panda''.<ref>{{worldcat|oclc=3047438|name=Trailing the Giant Panda}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v124/n3138/abs/124944b0.html|title=Review: ''Trailing the Giant Panda''|journal=Nature|date=21 December 1929|volume=124|issue=3138|pages=944|doi=10.1038/124944b0|bibcode=1929Natur.124R.944.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|jstor=1784124|title=Review: ''Trailing the Giant Panda'' by Theodore Roosevelt & Kermit Roosevelt|date=February 1930|journal=[[The Geographical Journal]]|volume=75|issue=2|pages=183–185|doi=10.2307/1784124}}</ref> Part of Suydam Cutting's 1940 book ''The Fire Ox and Other Years'' deals with the Kelley-Roosevelts expedition.
